Perfect — that actually sharpens the diagnosis a lot.

👉 Since KMS encryption is mandatory, your test strategy and fix need a slight adjustment.

⸻

🎯 What this changes

You cannot use:
	•	❌ unencrypted objects
	•	❌ SSE-S3

So your tests must always include:
	•	✅ SSE-KMS encryption

⸻

✅ Updated Debug Strategy (Console-Based)

🔬 Step 1 — Still do your isolation test (IMPORTANT)

Create:

👉 Test destination bucket WITHOUT WORM (but same KMS requirement)

Then:
	•	Keep SSE-KMS enabled
	•	Use same replication role
	•	Use same KMS key (or equivalent)

Upload test object:
	•	SSE-KMS enabled
	•	No Object Lock

👉 If replication works:
CONFIRMED → WORM is the issue (not KMS)

⸻

🔥 Now fix for WORM + KMS together

⸻

✅ PART 1 — IAM Role (MOST CRITICAL)

Go to:

👉 IAM → Roles → your replication role

Add BOTH:

{
  "Effect": "Allow",
  "Action": [
    "s3:GetObjectRetention",
    "s3:GetObjectLegalHold"
  ],
  "Resource": "*"
}


⸻

AND confirm KMS permissions exist:

{
  "Effect": "Allow",
  "Action": [
    "kms:Decrypt",
    "kms:Encrypt",
    "kms:ReEncrypt*",
    "kms:GenerateDataKey*"
  ],
  "Resource": "*"
}

👉 Even if infra “handles KMS”, your role still needs these actions.

⸻

✅ PART 2 — Replication Rule (Console)

Go to:

👉 S3 → Source bucket → Management → Replication → Edit

Ensure:
	•	✅ Destination bucket set
	•	✅ Encryption enabled for destination
	•	Select destination KMS key
	•	✅ Replicate object lock metadata (CRITICAL)

⸻

⚠️ Subtle but IMPORTANT

If you don’t explicitly set KMS in replication rule:

👉 replication may fail silently for KMS objects

So ensure:
	•	“Change object encryption” → Enabled
	•	Destination KMS key explicitly selected

⸻

✅ PART 3 — Destination Bucket

Go to:

👉 S3 → Destination bucket → Properties

Confirm:
	•	✅ Object Lock = Enabled
	•	✅ Versioning = Enabled

⸻

✅ PART 4 — Bucket Policy

Ensure destination bucket allows:
	•	s3:ReplicateObject
	•	s3:ReplicateDelete
	•	s3:ReplicateTags

👉 And NOT blocked by encryption conditions like:

"Condition": {
  "StringEquals": {
    "s3:x-amz-server-side-encryption": "aws:kms"
  }
}

(These sometimes break replication if misconfigured)

⸻

🧪 FINAL TEST (REAL CASE)

Upload object with:
	•	✅ SSE-KMS
	•	✅ Object Lock retention

In console:
	•	Upload → expand:
	•	Encryption → choose KMS
	•	Object Lock → set retention (1 day)

⸻

🔍 What you should now see

Stage	Before Fix	After Fix
Replication trigger	❌	✅
CloudTrail Encrypt	❌	✅
Object copied	❌	✅


⸻

🧠 Why your issue happens

Combination of:
	•	WORM enabled → requires extra S3 permissions
	•	KMS mandatory → requires explicit encryption handling
	•	Missing either → replication never starts

⸻

🎯 Most likely missing combo in your case

👉 Not just one — but this pair:

❌ Missing:
	•	s3:GetObjectRetention / LegalHold
	•	OR replication rule missing Object Lock metadata

PLUS possibly:
	•	KMS not explicitly set in replication rule

⸻

🚀 Clean Fix Summary

App side (YOU):
	•	✅ Add Object Lock permissions to IAM role
	•	✅ Enable Object Lock replication
	•	✅ Explicitly configure KMS in replication rule
	•	✅ Ensure bucket policy allows replication

Infra (just verify):
	•	✅ KMS key allows your role

